<body>
  <div class="container">
    <div class="header">
      <h1>LLM Chat (llama.cpp)</h1>
      <p>Complete Guide & Documentation</p>
    </div>

    <div class="section open">
      <div class="section-header" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">
        <div class="section-icon"><i class="fa fa-play"></i></div>
        <div class="section-title"><h2>Getting Started</h2><p>Quick overview of using LLM Chat</p></div>
        <i class="fa fa-chevron-down"></i>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>What is this app?</h3>
        <p>This app launches <strong>llama-server</strong> (from llama.cpp) on an HPC GPU node. It provides a browser-based chat interface and an OpenAI-compatible API for running large language models locally with full GPU acceleration.</p>
        <h3>Quick Start</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Select a model</strong> — Choose a system-wide model or enter the path to your own GGUF file</li>
          <li><strong>Configure resources</strong> — Select queue, hours, memory, and number of GPUs</li>
          <li><strong>Launch the job</strong> — Click "Launch" and wait for the model to load</li>
          <li><strong>Connect</strong> — Click the green "Connect to LLM Chat" button and start chatting!</li>
        </ol>
        <div class="box info"><i class="fa fa-info-circle"></i><div><strong>No SSH tunnel needed!</strong> This app connects directly through the cluster's reverse proxy. Just click "Connect" and you're in.</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">
        <div class="section-icon purple"><i class="fa fa-download"></i></div>
        <div class="section-title"><h2>Working with Models</h2><p>How to download and use GGUF models</p></div>
        <i class="fa fa-chevron-down"></i>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>Model Format</h3>
        <p>llama.cpp uses models in <strong>GGUF format</strong>. You can download them from <a href="https://huggingface.co/models?search=gguf" target="_blank" style="color:#3b82f6;">Hugging Face</a>.</p>

        <h3>Downloading Models</h3>
        <p>SSH to a login node and download to your scratch space:</p>
        <h4>Step 1: Create your models directory</h4>
        <div class="code">mkdir -p /lustre/nvwulf/scratch/$USER/models
cd /lustre/nvwulf/scratch/$USER/models</div>
        <h4>Step 2: Download a model</h4>
        <p>Choose one of the methods below:</p>
<div style="background:#f8fafc;border:1px solid #e2e8f0;border-radius:10px;padding:18px;margin:14px 0;">
  <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;">
    <span style="background:#3b82f6;color:white;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;padding:3px 8px;border-radius:4px;text-transform:uppercase;">Option A</span>
    <strong style="font-size:14px;color:#1e293b;">wget (simple)</strong>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:13px;color:#64748b;margin:0 0 10px;">Direct download — good for single files.</p>
  <div class="code" style="font-size:12px;"># Llama 3.2 3B (~2 GB)
wget https://huggingface.co/bartowski/Llama-3.2-3B-Instruct-GGUF/resolve/main/Llama-3.2-3B-Instruct-Q4_K_M.gguf

# Mistral 7B (~4 GB)
wget https://huggingface.co/TheBloke/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2-GGUF/resolve/main/mistral-7b-instruct-v0.2.Q4_K_M.gguf</div>
</div>
<div style="background:#f0fdf4;border:1px solid #bbf7d0;border-radius:10px;padding:18px;margin:14px 0;">
  <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;margin-bottom:10px;">
    <span style="background:#22c55e;color:white;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;padding:3px 8px;border-radius:4px;text-transform:uppercase;">Option B</span>
    <strong style="font-size:14px;color:#1e293b;">Hugging Face CLI (recommended)</strong>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:13px;color:#64748b;margin:0 0 10px;">Reliable downloads with resume support.</p>
  <div class="code" style="font-size:12px;"># Load the HuggingFace module
module load huggingface/1.2.3

# Qwen 2.5 7B (~4.5 GB)
hf download Qwen/Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct-GGUF \
--local-dir .</div>
</div>
        <p>Then when launching the app, select <strong>"No - Use my own model"</strong> and enter the full path to the .gguf file.</p>

        <h3>Recommended Models</h3>
        <p>For your RTX PRO 6000 GPUs (98 GB VRAM each):</p>
        <table>
          <tr><th>Model</th><th>Size</th><th>VRAM</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Llama 3.2 3B Q4</strong></td><td>2 GB</td><td>~3 GB</td><td>Quick tests, simple tasks</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Mistral 7B Q4</strong></td><td>4 GB</td><td>~6 GB</td><td>General purpose, good quality</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Llama 3.1 70B Q4</strong></td><td>40 GB</td><td>~44 GB</td><td>High quality, complex reasoning</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>DeepSeek-R1 70B Q4</strong></td><td>40 GB</td><td>~44 GB</td><td>Reasoning, math, code</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Llama 3.1 405B Q4</strong></td><td>230 GB</td><td>~240 GB</td><td>State-of-art (needs 3+ GPUs)</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3>Quantization Guide</h3>
        <p>GGUF models come in different quantization levels. Lower = smaller file + less VRAM, but slightly lower quality:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="inline-code">Q4_K_M</span> — Best balance of size, speed, and quality (recommended)</li>
          <li><span class="inline-code">Q5_K_M</span> — Slightly better quality, ~25% larger</li>
          <li><span class="inline-code">Q8_0</span> — Near-original quality, ~2x larger than Q4</li>
          <li><span class="inline-code">Q2_K</span> — Smallest, noticeable quality loss (not recommended)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Finding Models on Hugging Face</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <a href="https://huggingface.co/models?search=gguf" target="_blank" style="color:#3b82f6;">huggingface.co/models</a></li>
          <li>Search for the model name + "GGUF" (e.g., "Llama 3.1 70B GGUF")</li>
          <li>Look for uploaders like <strong>bartowski</strong>, <strong>TheBloke</strong>, or the official model author</li>
          <li>Download the Q4_K_M variant for the best balance</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">
        <div class="section-icon orange"><i class="fa fa-cog"></i></div>
        <div class="section-title"><h2>Admin Guide (HPC Admin Only)</h2><p>Adding system-wide models for all users</p></div>
        <i class="fa fa-chevron-down"></i>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>System Model Directory</h3>
        <p>System-wide GGUF models are stored in:</p>
        <div class="code">/lustre/nvwulf/software/llama.cpp/models/</div>

        <h3>Adding a New System Model</h3>
        <h4>Step 1: Download the GGUF file</h4>
        <div class="code">cd /lustre/nvwulf/software/llama.cpp/models/
wget https://huggingface.co/bartowski/Llama-3.2-3B-Instruct-GGUF/resolve/main/Llama-3.2-3B-Instruct-Q4_K_M.gguf
chmod a+r *.gguf</div>

        <h4>Step 2: Verify</h4>
        <div class="code">ls -lh /lustre/nvwulf/software/llama.cpp/models/*.gguf</div>

        <h4>Step 3: Update form.yml (optional)</h4>
        <p>To let users pick specific system models from a dropdown, update the <span class="inline-code">use_system_model</span> options in <span class="inline-code">form.yml.erb</span>.</p>

        <div class="box info"><i class="fa fa-info-circle"></i><div>Currently the app picks the first .gguf file it finds in the system models directory. To support multiple system models, update <span class="inline-code">script.sh.erb</span> to accept a model selection from the form.</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <div class="section-header" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">
        <div class="section-icon red"><i class="fa fa-wrench"></i></div>
        <div class="section-title"><h2>Troubleshooting</h2><p>Common issues and how to fix them</p></div>
        <i class="fa fa-chevron-down"></i>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <h3>"Connect" opens a blank page or error</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>The model may still be loading into GPU memory — large models (70B+) can take 1-2 minutes</li>
          <li>Wait 30 seconds and refresh the page</li>
          <li>Check the session log in the OOD dashboard for errors</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Model not found at launch</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Check that the GGUF file path is correct and the file exists</li>
          <li>Only <span class="inline-code">.gguf</span> format is supported — Ollama models, PyTorch, or safetensors won't work</li>
          <li>If using system models, verify files exist in <span class="inline-code">/lustre/nvwulf/software/llama.cpp/models/</span></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Slow responses</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Ensure <strong>GPU layers</strong> is set to "All (recommended)" in the form</li>
          <li>Check that you requested enough GPUs for your model size</li>
          <li>Try a smaller model or lower quantization (Q4 instead of Q8)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Out of memory</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>The model is too large for the allocated GPU(s)</li>
          <li>Try a smaller quantization: Q4_K_M instead of Q8_0</li>
          <li>Request more GPUs — each RTX PRO 6000 has 98 GB VRAM</li>
          <li>For 70B models: 1 GPU is enough with Q4. For 405B: use 3-4 GPUs</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Job fails immediately</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Check <span class="inline-code">llama-server.log</span> in the job output directory</li>
          <li>Ensure the llama.cpp module loads correctly: <span class="inline-code">module load llama.cpp/8184</span></li>
          <li>Verify <span class="inline-code">llama-server</span> is in your PATH after loading the module</li>
        </ul>

